WHEREAS, a comprehensive and transparent study is necessary to evaluate whether
a coordinated public approach to land assembly, environmental remediation, and
redevelopment would serve the best interests of residents of New Orleans East and the state
of Louisiana.
THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
Legislature of Louisiana does hereby create the Expropriation and Acquisition for Strategic
Transformation (E.A.S.T.) Task Force to study the legal feasibility, procedural requirements,
costs, and public benefits associated with the feasibility of expropriating and redeveloping
certain vacant, blighted, or undeveloped properties in New Orleans East and to report its
findings and recommendations to the legislature by March 1, 2027.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall prioritize approaches that
utilize publicly owned and tax-adjudicated properties, encourage voluntary acquisition where
feasible, limit expropriation to properties that are vacant, abandoned, or legally determined
to be blighted, and ensure that any use of expropriation serves a clear and documented public
purpose.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the legislature recommends that the task force
include consideration of the following:
(1) Applicable constitutional and statutory provisions governing expropriation in this
state.
(2) Limitations on expropriation for economic development purposes.
(3) Requirements for establishing and documenting blight or public necessity.
(4) Due process requirements and procedural safeguards.
(5) Mapping and classification of parcels including tax-adjudicated properties.
(6) Prevalence of heirs' property and clouded title issues.
(7) Mechanisms for quieting title and facilitating lawful acquisition.
(8) Methods for determining fair market value.
(9) Procedures for depositing compensation into the registry of the court.
(10) Administrative considerations for resolving competing ownership claims.
(11) Extent of illegal dumping and environmental hazards.
(12) Estimated costs of remediation and site preparation.
(13) Opportunities for state and federal environmental funding support.
